We have

$$
\begin{aligned}
z^3 &= 1 \\[6pt]
z^3 &= \cos 0 + {\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}\sin 0 \hspace{5.2em}\end{aligned}
$$

Hence, using de Moivre's theorem, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\hspace{9.9em} z &= (\cos 0 + {\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}\sin 0)^\frac{1}{3} \\[5pt]
&= \cos\Big(\dfrac{2k\pi}{3}\Big) + {\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}\sin\Big(\dfrac{2k\pi}{3}\Big) \hspace{3em} [\text{for $k = 0,1,2$}]\end{aligned}
$$

Hence the roots of the equation $z^3 = 1$ are

$$
\begin{aligned}
k = 0 &: \hspace{0.525em}\answer{z = \cos 0 + {\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}\sin 0 = 1} \\[7pt]
k = 1 &: \hspace{0.525em}\answer{z = \cos\Big(\dfrac{2\pi}{3}\Big) + {\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}\sin \Big(\dfrac{2\pi}{3}\Big) = -\dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}{\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}} \\[10pt]
k = 2 &: \hspace{0.525em}\answer{z = \cos\Big(\dfrac{4\pi}{3}\Big) + {\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}\sin \Big(\dfrac{4\pi}{3}\Big) = -\dfrac{1}{2} - \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}{\mathrm{\hspace{0.05em}i}\mkern 1mu}}\end{aligned}
$$

- Expand the expression

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (x-z)(x-z^*)&=x^2-zx-z^*x+zz^*\\[6pt]
      &=x^2-(z+z^*)x+zz^* \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  If we let $z=a+bi$ then $z^*=a-bi$.
  We can now simplify $z+z^*$ and $zz^*$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  z+z^*&=a+bi+a-bi\\[6pt]
      &=2a\\[6pt]
      &=2\text{Re}(z) \tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
      zz^*&=(a+bi)(a-bi)\\[6pt]
      &=a^2-b^2i^2\\[6pt]
      &=a^2+b^2\\[6pt]
      &=|z|^2 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Substituting these expressions into the expansion above we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (x-z)(x-z^*)&=x^2-(z+z^*)x+zz^*\\[6pt]
      &=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{x^2-2\text{Re}(z)x+|z|^2} \hspace{1em} \text{... as required.}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- Recognise that a real polynomial has complex roots in  conjugate pairs.
  We can write the remaining roots of the polynomial

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      z_3=z_1^*&=\sqrt{2}\,\text{cis}\,{\tfrac{-\pi}{4}} &\hspace{2em} & z_4=z_2^*=2+i
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can now write the polynomial in factorised form using the roots

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      z^4+az^3+bz^2+cz+d&=(z-z_1)(z-z_2)(z-z_3)(z-z_4)\\[6pt]
      &=(z-z_1)(z-z_1^*)(z-z_2)(z-z_2^*)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can use the identity we proved part(a) to rewrite the factors

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{red}{(z-z_1)(z-z_1^*)}\textcolor{blue}{(z-z_2)(z-z_2^*)}&=\textcolor{red}{(z^2-2\text{Re}{(z_1)}z+|z_1|^2)}\textcolor{blue}{(z^2-2\text{Re}{(z_2)}z+|z_2|^2)} 
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack}\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Next we can identify the elements we need complete the expansion

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \text{Re}(z_1)&=\sqrt{2}\times \cos{\tfrac{\pi}{4}} &\hspace{2em} & |z_1|^2=\sqrt{2}^2\\[6pt]
  \textcolor{white}{\text{Re}(z_1)}&=\sqrt{2}\times \tfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} &\hspace{2em} &  \textcolor{white}{|z_1|^2}=\textcolor{orange}{2}\\[6pt]
  \textcolor{white}{\text{Re}(z_1)}&=\textcolor{red}{1} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
  \text{Re}(z_2)&=\textcolor{blue}{2} &\hspace{2em} & |z_2|^2=(\sqrt{2^2+1^2})^2\\[6pt]
  \textcolor{white}{\text{Re}(z_2)}& &\hspace{2em} &  \textcolor{white}{|z_2|^2}=\textcolor{green}{5} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can now substitute these values into the expansion above

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &(z^2-2\text{Re}{(z_1)}z+|z_1|^2)(z^2-2\text{Re}{(z_2)}z+|z_2|^2)\\[6pt]
      &=(z^2-2\times \textcolor{red}{1}z+\textcolor{orange}{2})(z^2-2\times \textcolor{blue}{2}z+\textcolor{green}{5})
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can now expand this expression and simplify

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &(z^2-2z+2)(z^2-4z+5)\\[6pt]
      &=z^4-4z^3+5z^2-2z^3+8z^2-10z+2z^2-8z+10\\[6pt]
      &=z^4-6z^3+15z^2-18z+10
  \end{align*}
  $$

  $\answer{\text{Therefore }a=-6,\, b=15,\, c=-18 \text{ and } d=10}$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We know, due to the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra, that a polynomial of order $3$ must have $3$ roots.
  Also, $p(z)$ is a real polynomial, this means its coefficients are real numbers and that any complex roots must come in conjugate pairs.
  Hence we can write down the second root as $\answer{3-4i}$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \textcolor{white}{placeholder}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We have one root remaining, it must be real.
  Looking at the polynomial we can see we have been given the first and last coefficient.
  Consider the formulae for the sum and products of the roots of a polynomial

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \text{Sum of roots}&=\frac{-a_{n-1}}{a_n} \hspace{3em}\text{Product of roots}=\frac{(-1)^na_{0}}{a_n} 
  \end{align*}
  $$

  $n$ is the order of the polynomial, which in this case is $3$.
  $a_n$, where $n=3$ refers to the coefficient of the $z^3$ term and $a_0$ refers to the constant term.
  We can write down the values

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      a_3&=2\\[6pt]
      a_0&=-75\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This is enough information to find the value of the product of the roots.
  Hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \text{Product of roots}&=\frac{(-1)^na_{0}}{a_n}\\[6pt]
      &=\frac{(-1)^3\times (-75)}{2}\\[6pt]
      &=\frac{75}{2}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  If we call the third root $z_3$ we can form an equation which we can solve on our G.D.C.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (3+4i)(3-4i)z_3&=\frac{75}{2}\\[6pt]
      z_3&=\answer{\dfrac{3}{2}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We can use the roots from part (a) to write out $p(z)$ in factorised form

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (z-(3+4i))(z-(3-4i)(z-\tfrac{3}{2})&=0\\[6pt]
       \textcolor{red}{(z-3-4i)(z-3+4i)}(z-\tfrac{3}{2})&=0\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  There is a very useful identity, worth memorising, that is helpful when expanding brackets of $\textcolor{red}{\text{this}}$ form

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (z-w)(z-w^*)&=z^2-2\text{Re}(w)(z)+|w|^2
  \end{align*}
  $$

  In our case $w=3+4i$ therefore

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      |w|^2&=(\sqrt{3^2+4^2})^2\\[6pt]
      &=5^2\\[6pt]
      &=25
  \end{align*}
  $$

  And

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \text{Re}(w)&=\text{Re}(3+4i)\\[6pt]
      &=3
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Putting these results together we can expand the $\textcolor{red}{\text{red}}$ part of the factorised form to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
       \textcolor{red}{(z-3-4i)(z-3+4i)}(z-\tfrac{3}{2})&=0\\[6pt]
       \textcolor{red}{(z^2-2 \times 3 z+25)}(z-\tfrac{3}{2})&=0\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now we can expand the rest of the expression to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      z^3-6z^2+25z-\tfrac{3}{2}z^2+9z-\tfrac{75}{2}&=0
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can multiply throughout by $2$ and simplify to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2z^3-12z^2+50z-3z^2+18z-75&=0\\[6pt]
      2x^3-15z^2+68z-75&=0\\[6pt]
      p(z)=2x^3-15z^2+68z-75
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore $\answer{a=-15}$ and $\answer{b=68}\hspace{0.525em}$.

